Model validation using Leave-one-out (LOO) Cross-Validation

Model validation is difficult in general, let alone in a mixed model context. The best way to evaluate model performance is through the use out-of-sample validation, or by fitting a model to new data. However, this not feasible in most situations. The best alternative is to use an in-sample validation procedure by iteratively refitting models to subsets of the data (e.g. using K-folds or LOO), whereby the model uses a portion of the data to train the model and remaining data to test the model fit.

The K-folds procedure articulated in Boyce etal. (2002) is generally overly optimistic in that it doesn’t take into conderation the random effects or heirarchical levels of the model. The subsets should either sample proportionally across all individuals or by removing an individual one-by-one.

Here, we will show you how to implement LOO in a frequentist context using code authored by ourselves and Mark Hebblewhite.

# Load the necessary libraries
library(lme4)

# Source LOO script
source('./Source/LOO.R')

# Load the data
d <- read.csv("./Data/RSFdata_std_rand10x.csv")

Currently, you will need to specify the formula’s for both the mixed and standard GLM. Both model formulas should be the same with the exception of the inclusion of the a single random effect in the former.

# Define the formulas to validate
formMix <- 'Used ~ slope + elev + 
  dist_dlv + dist_lbv + dist_blv +
  dist_paved + dist_unpaved + 
  dist_rivers +
  Dry:dist_rivers + 
  NDVI +
  (1|ID)'
  
formNonMix <- 'Used ~ slope + elev + 
  dist_dlv + dist_lbv + dist_blv +
  dist_paved + dist_unpaved + 
  dist_rivers +
  Dry:dist_rivers + 
  NDVI'

The loo function performs the leave-one-out operation by cycling through and pulling one individual out, fitting a model, and comparing model fit with the data from a single individual.

# Run the LOO cross-validation based
# on model specifications
out <- loo(d, formMix, formNonMix, thin=1, 
           rE = 'ID')

To table precision, bias, and correlation metrics.

# Table output from LOO run
(tab <- tableLOO(out))
# Mean correlation in LOO
knitr::kable(tab <- tableLOO(out))
Precision Bias Correlation
Queen 7.02e-05 0 -0.0162480
Gabs 2.02e-05 0 0.3709919
Cilla 1.13e-05 0 0.4326640
Mvubu 2.49e-05 0 0.6615909
Toni 7.90e-06 0 0.2344400
Pepper 7.77e-05 0 0.0281109

Mean correlation tells us on average how well the model performs in the LOO cross-validation (value from 0 - 1, with higher values indicating stronger fit).

# Mean correlation in LOO
mean(abs(tab$Correlation))
## [1] 0.2906743

And finally, to visualize the fits by individual…

# Plot function for LOO fits
plotLOO(out)
